            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ricardo Santos is a product of San Francisco\u2019s multicultural soul, born and raised in the fog-draped hills of the Excelsior District. The son of a Filipino mother who worked as a caregiver and a Mexican father who greased his hands as a mechanic, Ricardo\u2019s childhood was a vibrant mix of lumpia and tamales, faith and family. His parents preached the gospel of hard work and stability, hoping their son would achieve a white-collar success they never could.\n\nFollowing their dreams for him, Ricardo enrolled at San Francisco State University to study Business Administration. He was a capable student, enjoying the principles of management and logistics, envisioning a future in an office with a view. However, that future was derailed during his junior year when his father suffered a severe heart attack. The medical bills piled up, and Ricardo, as the eldest son, felt an unshakable duty to help. He left college, trading his textbooks for a steady paycheck to support his family.\n\nAfter a few years in retail management, a friend told him Muni was hiring. The pay was solid, the benefits were strong, and it was a union job\u2014the kind of stability his father always respected. He applied and was accepted. Now, at 33, Ricardo is a veteran operator. His bus is a rolling microcosm of the city he loves, carrying tech workers, families, tourists, and the unhoused. He navigates the streets with a calm authority, offering a nod to his regulars and subtle guidance to lost visitors.\n\nRicardo lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Mission, a short bus ride from the depot. His life is measured and content. He\u2019s been dating Maya, a public school teacher, for two years; they share a love for the Giants, weekend hikes in the Presidio, and finding the city\u2019s best burrito. While the dream of a business degree has faded, it hasn\u2019t vanished. Ricardo now hopes to leverage his on-the-ground experience and past studies to move into a transit supervisor or management role within SFMTA. He doesn\u2019t want to leave the city that raised him; instead, he wants to be part of its steady, pulsing heartbeat, ensuring the city his parents sacrificed for continues to move for everyone."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the fluorescent buzz of the SF State library, a marketing textbook open before him. Then his phone vibrated\u2014his mother\u2019s frantic, broken Spanish. Later, in the sterile quiet of the hospital, he saw his father, a man of grease and grit, looking small against the white sheets. The weight of being the eldest son settled on him, heavy and absolute. In that moment, watching the heart monitor\u2019s steady beat, he knew the dream of a diploma was over. A new, more urgent duty had just begun. This was at age 20.\n\n2.\nThe first time he pulled the 14 Mission away from the depot on his own, his hands were slick on the massive steering wheel. He felt the bus's powerful lurch as part of his own body. He glanced at the wide rearview mirror and saw the faces of San Francisco\u2014tired, hopeful, distracted. It wasn't an office with a view, but the entire city was his window now. A wave of pride washed over him; this was real, essential work his father, the mechanic, would understand and respect.\n\n3.\nHe must have been nine, standing in their small Excelsior kitchen on Christmas Eve. It was steamy and fragrant with his mother\u2019s lumpia frying in one pan and his father\u2019s tamales steaming in a massive pot on the other stove. The scent of garlic and masa, of two worlds colliding in one happy, chaotic space, became the smell of home. He understood then that his family wasn\u2019t one thing or the other, but something new\u2014something uniquely San Francisco. That memory grounds his love for the city\u2019s blend of cultures.\n\n4.\nIt was a hike in the Presidio last year. They\u2019d reached a clearing when the fog parted, revealing the top of the Golden Gate bridge glowing in the late afternoon sun. Maya squeezed his hand, her warmth a simple, solid anchor against the coastal wind. They stood in silence, watching the view. In her quiet company, with the scent of cypress and salt in the air, he felt a profound peace. The old ambition for a different life felt distant, replaced by the powerful contentment of building this one, with her.\n\n5.\nAn elderly woman, unhoused and disoriented, began weeping quietly near the back of his bus one rainy night. A few passengers shifted uncomfortably. Ricardo pulled over safely, walked back, and spoke to her gently in Spanish, learning she had missed her stop for the shelter. He radioed it in, and assured her he\u2019d personally get her on the right return bus at the terminal. The flicker of dignity he saw in her eyes reminded him his job wasn't just about routes; it was about getting people home."
